l, social, and political context. Postgenomics, they argue, forces a rethinking of the genome itself, and opens new territory for conversations between the social sciences, humanities, and life sciences.Contributors. Russ Altman, Rachel A. Ankeny, Catherine Bliss, John Dupré, Michael Fortun, Evelyn Fox Keller, Sabina Leonelli, Adrian Mackenzie, Margot Moinester, Aaron Panofsky, Sarah S. Richardson, Sara Shostak, Hallam Stevens  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aGenetic engineeringxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aGenomicsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aHuman gene mapping. 7aSCIENCE / Philosophy & Social Aspects.2bisacsh1 aPanofsky, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMackenzie, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBliss, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeller, Evelyn Fox, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, Hallam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupré, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoinester, Margot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortun, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnkeny, Rachel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Sarah S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAltman, Russ, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeonelli, Sabina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShostak, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Sarah S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevens, Hallam, eeditor.